# UI Styling Playbook

## Precedence

Reference-only guidance; not authoritative.
For global conflict order, see `rules-index.mdc`.

This playbook complements `ui-styling-rules.mdc` with practical examples.
Use it as implementation guidance, not as a duplicate source of enforcement.

## 1) Component-First Authoring

Default to Shadcn/Radix components for interactive controls.

### Prefer

- `<Button>` over `<button>`
- `<Input>` over `<input>`
- `<Textarea>` over `<textarea>`
- `<Select>` over native `<select>`
- `<Checkbox>`, `<RadioGroup>`, `<Switch>`
- `<Dialog>` / `<Sheet>`, `<Popover>` / `<DropdownMenu>`

### Allowed Native Exceptions

- Semantic structure: `<header>`, `<main>`, `<section>`, `<article>`, `<footer>`
- HTML media/graphics: `<video>`, `<audio>`, `<canvas>`
- Form edge-cases: hidden/file inputs when required

### Example

```tsx
// Avoid
<button className="px-4 py-2 bg-primary rounded">Submit</button>;

// Prefer
import { Button } from '@/components/ui/button';

<Button>Submit</Button>;
```

## 2) Theme Token and Variant Strategy

Prefer semantic tokens and component variants for durable product UI.

### Prefer

- `bg-background`, `bg-card`, `bg-muted`
- `text-foreground`, `text-muted-foreground`
- `border-border`, `text-destructive`
- Built-in variants instead of one-off class stacks

### Avoid

- Hardcoding long-lived meaning with literal palettes in app UI

```tsx
// Avoid
<div className="bg-white text-black border-gray-200">...</div>

// Prefer
<div className="bg-card text-card-foreground border border-border">...</div>
```

## 3) Loading-State Patterns

For async data, prefer skeleton-first loading states.

### Baseline Flow

1. `loading` -> skeleton
2. `error` -> error state
3. `empty` -> empty state
4. `success` -> content

### Example

```tsx
if (loading) return <HistorySkeleton count={8} />;
if (error) return <ErrorState />;
if (!data?.length) return <EmptyState />;
return <Content data={data} />;
```

### Skeleton Notes

- Match skeleton layout to final content layout.
- Prefer existing skeleton primitives before creating new ones.
- Keep spacing and hierarchy realistic to reduce visual jank.

## 4) Accessibility in UI Composition

For motion/interaction baselines (touch target, reduced motion, pseudo-clickable behavior),
follow `frontend-motion-interaction-governance.mdc`.

In this playbook, focus on composition-level a11y:

- Use semantic controls and labels by default.
- Ensure form inputs are associated with labels.
- Use `aria-hidden="true"` only for decorative content.

```tsx
<Label htmlFor="email">Email</Label>
<Input id="email" type="email" />
```

## 5) Interaction Design Patterns

### Progressive Disclosure

Start simple, reveal sophistication through interaction.

```tsx
// Basic options visible; advanced behind expandable section
<div>
  <MainOptions />
  <Collapsible>
    <CollapsibleTrigger asChild>
      <Button variant="ghost">Advanced options</Button>
    </CollapsibleTrigger>
    <CollapsibleContent>
      <AdvancedOptions />
    </CollapsibleContent>
  </Collapsible>
</div>
```

### Button Hierarchy

Not every action deserves a primary button — use variant hierarchy to guide attention.

```tsx
// Primary action stands out; secondary recedes
<div className="flex gap-3">
  <Button>Save changes</Button>
  <Button variant="ghost">Cancel</Button>
</div>
```

### Empty States

Design empty states that teach the interface, not just say "nothing here."

```tsx
// Avoid: <p>No items found.</p>
// Prefer:
<EmptyState
  title="No projects yet"
  description="Create your first project to get started."
  action={<Button>Create project</Button>}
/>
```

## 6) UX Writing

- Make every word earn its place — remove filler and redundant labels.
- Do not repeat information users can already see (e.g. a heading that restates the page title).
- Labels and descriptions should help users act, not describe the obvious.

```tsx
// Avoid: redundant intro
<h2>Your Projects</h2>
<p>This is a list of all your projects.</p>

// Prefer: actionable context
<h2>Your Projects</h2>
<p>Select a project to continue editing, or create a new one.</p>
```

## 7) Design Quality Anti-patterns

Common patterns that make UI feel generic or AI-generated. Avoid these:

- **Glassmorphism everywhere** — blur effects, glass cards, and glow borders used decoratively rather than purposefully.
- **Identical card grids** — same-sized cards with icon + heading + text repeated endlessly.
- **Card-in-card nesting** — visual noise; flatten the hierarchy.
- **Decorative sparklines** — tiny charts that look sophisticated but convey nothing meaningful.
- **Rounded rectangles with generic drop shadows** — safe, forgettable default.
- **Uniform spacing** — same padding everywhere with no rhythm or grouping.
- **Gradient text on headings** — decorative rather than meaningful; also an accessibility concern (see motion governance §4).

When reviewing UI, ask: does this feel intentionally designed for the context, or could it be any generic template?

## 8) PR Review Checklist (UI Composition)

- [ ] Interactive controls use design-system primitives (or documented exception)
- [ ] Styling uses semantic tokens/variants for long-lived semantics
- [ ] Button variants create clear action hierarchy
- [ ] Typography has clear weight/size hierarchy across heading, body, and label levels
- [ ] Layout avoids card-in-card nesting and monotonous equal spacing
- [ ] Empty states are actionable, not just "nothing here"
- [ ] Copy is concise and non-redundant
- [ ] Async content has skeleton/error/empty/success flow
- [ ] No generic anti-patterns from §7
- [ ] Composition guidance does not conflict with motion governance rule
